<FeaturePage
  tagline="Multi-Agent"
  title="Multiple Agents, One Codebase"
  description="Run multiple AI agents on the same codebase. The OS resolves file conflicts at write time — no locks, no message buses, no coordination code."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>

  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>
    You spawn two agents. One is refactoring the auth module. The other is adding a new API endpoint that imports from the auth module. Both agents edit <code>src/auth/middleware.js</code> within seconds of each other.
  </p>
  <p>Who wins?</p>
  <p>
    Without coordination, the last write wins and the first agent&rsquo;s work disappears. With traditional locking, the second agent blocks until the first finishes &mdash; and if the first agent takes 40 turns, that&rsquo;s 40 turns of idle time. With message buses, both agents need to understand a coordination protocol they were never trained on.
  </p>
  <p>
    ostk takes a different approach: agents write files normally. They don&rsquo;t know other agents exist. The OS detects conflicts at write time and resolves them without interrupting either agent.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>The daemon (<code>ostk listen</code>) is the anchor. It holds the process table, the scheduler, and the socket. Agents run as managed sessions inside the daemon with heartbeat monitoring, drain snapshots, and crash recovery.</p>
  <p>The scheduler LLM dispatches work by calling <code>spawn_agent</code> &mdash; a kernel tool that creates a managed worker session. The worker runs its turns, and the scheduler reaps it when done via <code>reap_agent</code>. The operator can also spawn workers directly:</p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code># Start the daemon
$ ostk listen

# Spawn workers from the CLI
$ ostk kernel spawn auth-refactor --model sonnet --budget 2 "Refactor auth to use JWT"
$ ostk kernel spawn add-endpoint --model sonnet --budget 2 "Add POST /api/teams endpoint"

# Watch the fleet
$ ostk kernel ps</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>Each agent works independently. They read files, run tests, write code. When their edits don&rsquo;t overlap, writes go through immediately. When they do overlap, the kernel resolves the conflict.</p>

  <h2>When conflicts happen</h2>
  <p>
    Every <code>file:edit()</code> specifies the text the agent expects to find. If that text no longer exists &mdash; another agent changed it &mdash; the edit fails and the resolution tiers engage.
  </p>

  <h2>How conflict resolution works</h2>
  <p>
    Conflict resolution is <strong>mechanical text diffing</strong>, not LLM-assisted. No model is called. The kernel classifies each conflict into one of three tiers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tier 1 &mdash; Auto-merge.</strong> The two edits touch different parts of the file, sufficiently far apart. The kernel applies both changes silently and logs the merge to audit. Neither agent is interrupted. This is the common case.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 2 &mdash; Assisted rebase.</strong> The edits are nearby or overlapping, but the total change is small. The kernel computes a mechanical rebase &mdash; it relocates the second agent&rsquo;s edit into the file as modified by the first, returning a suggested <code>file:edit()</code> with updated line references. No model call, no blocking.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier 3 &mdash; Manual.</strong> The changes are too large or structurally incompatible for mechanical resolution. The kernel returns the current file content and both agents&rsquo; intended changes. The agent re-reads and retries. If it cannot resolve it, the conflict escalates to the operator.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Failure modes:</strong> Tier 3 requires the agent to re-read and retry, costing tokens and time. Semantic conflicts (two agents change different files in ways that break each other&rsquo;s logic) are not caught &mdash; they surface at test time. Binary files skip resolution entirely and fall back to last-write-wins with an audit warning.
  </p>

  <h2>Crash recovery</h2>
  <p>Agents crash. Context exhaustion, SIGKILL, network timeouts, budget overruns. The OS expects this.</p>
  <p>Every agent writes a drain snapshot at every turn boundary &mdash; conversation history, token accounting, and full session config. When a worker crashes:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>The daemon&rsquo;s heartbeat monitor detects the stale heartbeat (>90s without update, process dead)</li>
    <li>The worker is removed from the session manager</li>
    <li>If a drain snapshot exists and the revival policy is <code>revive</code>, the daemon hot-rehydrates the session immediately &mdash; no restart needed</li>
    <li>The rehydrated worker resumes with its full conversation history intact</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Revival policy is per-agent, declared in the <a href="/docs/agentfile">Agentfile</a>:</p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code>LIMIT revival_policy revive   # auto-recover (default)
LIMIT revival_policy reap     # drop on crash
LIMIT revival_policy ask      # operator decides</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>Ask-pending lineages are resolved via <code>ostk lineage resolve &lt;id&gt; --revive</code> or <code>--reap</code>.</p>

  <h2>Sub-stacks</h2>
  <p>For multi-worker tasks that need blast-radius containment, the scheduler creates a sub-stack &mdash; an isolated group of sessions with its own audit log, drain directory, and token budget:</p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code># The scheduler calls spawn_stack to create an isolated scope
spawn_stack(scope="bugfix-27", prompt="Fix the auth race condition", budget=5.00)

# The sub-stack gets its own filesystem layout:
.ostk/stacks/bugfix-27/
  audit.jsonl    # scoped audit log
  drain/         # scoped drain snapshots
  inbox/         # commands from anchor
  nudges/        # reports to anchor</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>Budget overruns force-seal the sub-stack. The anchor and its scheduler are unaffected. This is hierarchical failure isolation &mdash; the blast radius stops at the sub-stack boundary.</p>

  <h2>Agent isolation</h2>
  <p>
    Each agent operates in its own context. Agents do not share conversation history, tool state, or memory. They share only the filesystem &mdash; the codebase itself.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No cross-talk</strong> &mdash; agent-1 cannot read agent-2&rsquo;s thoughts, prompt, or intermediate reasoning. They coordinate through the files they produce, the same way human developers coordinate through commits.</li>
    <li><strong>Independent failure</strong> &mdash; if agent-2 crashes, agent-1 continues unaffected. The daemon detects the crash via heartbeat and handles recovery automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Model mixing</strong> &mdash; each agent can use a different model. Run a cheap model for linting while a frontier model handles the complex refactor. The OS coordinates their writes the same way regardless of which model is behind each agent.</li>
    <li><strong>Process isolation</strong> &mdash; agents with <code>ISOLATION nono</code> in their <a href="/docs/agentfile">Agentfile</a> run inside a Landlock/Seatbelt sandbox. Filesystem access is restricted to an allowlist at the syscall level. See <a href="/docs/pins">Capability Pins</a> for the two-layer enforcement model.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fleet commands</h2>
  <p>The <a href="/docs/commands">command reference</a> covers the full surface. Key fleet operations:</p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code># Start the daemon (the anchor)
$ ostk listen

# Spawn a background worker
$ ostk kernel spawn lint-fix --model sonnet --budget 2 "Fix all ESLint warnings"

# Wait for a worker to finish
$ ostk kernel await lint-fix

# Show fleet status
$ ostk kernel ps

# Reap dead agents from the process table
$ ostk kernel reap

# Resolve an ask-pending session
$ ostk lineage resolve worker-3 --revive</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>Inside the daemon, the scheduler LLM manages workers via MCP tools: <code>spawn_agent</code>, <code>reap_agent</code>, <code>spawn_stack</code>, <code>seal_stack</code>. The scheduler decides when to spawn, what model to use, and when to reap &mdash; the operator sets policy via Agentfiles, the kernel enforces it.</p>

  <h2>Constraints</h2>
  <p>Multi-agent coordination is not magic. There are limits:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Conflict resolution works best on text files. Binary files fall back to last-write-wins with a warning.</li>
    <li>Semantic conflicts (two agents change different files in ways that break each other&rsquo;s logic) require test runs to catch. ostk does not understand your program&rsquo;s semantics &mdash; it coordinates at the file level.</li>
    <li>More agents means more potential conflicts. In practice, 2&ndash;4 agents on well-scoped tasks produce fewer conflicts than one agent doing everything.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Getting started</h2>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code>$ ostk init                  # one-time setup
$ ostk listen                # start the daemon
$ ostk kernel spawn task-a --model sonnet --budget 2 "Your first task"
$ ostk kernel spawn task-b --model sonnet --budget 2 "Your second task"
$ ostk kernel ps             # watch both</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>Coordination is on by default. There is no flag to enable it and no configuration file to edit.</p>

